# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nodemailer-email
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] The term **asynchronous** refers to two or more objects or events that do not exist or happen at the same time, that is, they are **not** synchronous.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] When multiple related things happen without any being dependent on the completion of previous happenings, they are asynchronous.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] In computing, the word "asynchronous" is used in two major contexts, as explained below.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] Asynchronous communication is a method of exchanging messages in which the sending, receiving, and processing of each message is not dependent on the sending, receipt, or processing of other messages.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] In asynchronous communication, each party receives and processes messages when convenient or possible to do so, rather than doing so immediately upon receipt.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] Additionally, messages may be sent without waiting for acknowledgement, with the understanding that if a problem occurs, the recipient will request corrections or otherwise handle the situation.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] Email is a type of asynchronous human communication.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] The recipient reads the email and responds to it (or not) at their convenience, not necessarily right away.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] All parties can continue to send and receive messages at any time.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] Emails don't have to be scheduled in a particular sequence.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] In asynchronous software, making a request, such as to a server, does not block other processes while waiting for the response.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] The software can continue performing other tasks.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] For example, in promise-based APIs, `Promise` objects are created for long operations.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] After the operation is complete, the promise is handled.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] With promises, the software doesn't have to wait for the operation to finish.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] Asynchronous software design expands upon the concept by building code that allows a program to ask that a task be performed alongside the original task (or tasks), without stopping to wait for the task to complete.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] When the secondary task is completed, the original task is notified using an agreed-upon mechanism so that it knows the work is done, and that the result, if any, is available.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] There are a number of programming techniques for implementing asynchronous software.
[src:nodemailer-email/asynchronous] See the article Asynchronous JavaScript for an introduction to them.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] An **email address** identifies a mailbox to which email messages are delivered.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] While early messaging systems used a variety of address formats, email addresses today follow a specific set of rules originally standardized by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in the 1980s, and updated by RFC 5322 and 6854.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The term "email address" in this article refers to just the *addr-spec* in Section 3.4 of RFC 5322.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The RFC defines *address* more broadly as either a *mailbox* or *group*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] A *mailbox* value can be either a *name-addr*, which contains a *display-name* and *addr-spec*, or the more common *addr-spec* alone.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] An email address, such as *jane.smith@example.com*, is made up of a local-part, the symbol @, and a *domain*, which may be either a domain name or an IP address enclosed in brackets.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Although the standard stipulates that the local-part is case-sensitive, it also urges that receiving hosts deliver messages in a case-independent manner, e.g., that the mail system in the domain *example.com* treat *Jane.Smith* as equivalent to *jane.smith*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] (Some mail systems even treat both as equivalent to *jane smith*.) Email systems often limit the user's choice of name to a subset of the characters permitted by the RFCs.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] With the introduction of internationalized domain names, efforts are progressing to permit non-ASCII characters in email addresses.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Due to the ubiquity of email today, email addresses are used as regular usernames by many websites and services that provide a user profile or account.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] For example, if a user wants to log in to their Xbox Live video gaming profile, they would use their email address as the username ID of their Microsoft account, even though the service in this case is not email.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] An email address consists of two parts, a local-part (sometimes a user name, but not always) and a domain.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] If the domain is a domain name rather than an IP address, then the SMTP client looks up the mail-exchange (MX) IP address of that domain name.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The general format of an email address is *local-part*@*domain*, e.g. jsmith@[192.168.1.2], *jsmith@example.com*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The SMTP client transmits the message to the mail exchange, which may forward it to another mail exchange, until it ultimately arrives at the host of the recipient's mail system.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The transmission of electronic mail from the sender's computer and between mail hosts in the Internet uses the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP), defined in RFC 5321 and 5322, and extensions such as RFC 6531.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The mailboxes may be accessed and managed by applications on personal computers, mobile devices or webmail sites using the SMTP protocol and either the Post Office Protocol (POP) or the Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP).
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] When transmitting email messages, mail user agents (MUAs) and mail transfer agents (MTAs) use the domain name system (DNS) to look up a resource record (RR) for the recipient's domain.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] A mail exchange resource record (MX record) contains the name of the recipient's mail server.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] In the absence of an MX record, an address record (whether A or AAAA) directly specifies the mail host.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The local-part of an email address has no significance for intermediate mail relay systems other than the final mailbox host.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Email senders and intermediate relay systems must not assume it to be case-insensitive, since the final mailbox host may or may not treat it as such.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] A single mailbox may receive mail for multiple email addresses, if configured by the administrator.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Conversely, a single email address may be the alias to a distribution list to many mailboxes.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Email aliases, electronic mailing lists, sub-addressing, and catch-all addresses (mailboxes that receive messages regardless of the local-part) are common patterns for achieving a variety of delivery goals.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The addresses contained in the header fields of an email message are not directly used by mail exchanges to deliver the message.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] In SMTP mail transfer, the sending system communicates the source and destination addresses; this information is sometimes called the "message envelope".
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] While the envelope and header addresses may be the same, this is not strictly required, and forged or "spoofed" email addresses are often seen in spam, phishing, and many other Internet-based scams.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] This has led to several initiatives aimed at making such forgeries of fraudulent emails easier to spot.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The format of an email address is *local-part@domain*, where the local-part may be up to 64 octets long and the domain may have a maximum of 255 octets.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The formal definitions are in RFC 5322 (sections 3.2.3 and 3.4.1) and RFC 5321—with a more readable form given in the informational RFC 3696 (written by J.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Klensin, the author of RFC 5321) and the associated errata.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] An email address also may have an associated "display-name" (Display Name) for the recipient, which precedes the address specification, surrounded by angled brackets in that case, for example: *Jane Smith <jane.smith@example.org>*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Email spammers and phishers will often use "Display Name spoofing" to trick their victims, by using a false Display Name, or by using a different email address as the Display Name.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Earlier forms of email addresses for other networks than the Internet included other notations, such as that required by X.400, and the UUCP *bang path* notation, in which the address was given in the form of a sequence of computers through which the message should be relayed.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] This was widely used for several years, but was superseded by the Internet standards promulgated by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The local-part of the email address may be unquoted or may be enclosed in quotation marks.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] If quoted, it may contain Space, Horizontal Tab (HT), any ASCII graphic except Backslash and Quote and a quoted-pair consisting of a Backslash followed by HT, Space or any ASCII graphic; it may also be split between lines anywhere that HT or Space appears.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] In contrast to unquoted local-parts, the addresses `".Jane.Doe"@example.com`, `"Jane.Doe."@example.com` and `"Jane..Doe"@example.com` are allowed.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The maximum total length of the local-part of an email address is 64 octets.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] In addition to the above ASCII characters, international characters above U+007F, encoded as UTF-8, are permitted by RFC 6531 when the EHLO specifies SMTPUTF8, though even mail systems that support SMTPUTF8 and 8BITMIME may restrict what characters to use when assigning local-parts.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] A local-part is either a Dot-string or a Quoted-string; it cannot be a combination.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Quoted strings and characters, however, are not commonly used.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] RFC 5321 also warns that "a host that expects to receive mail SHOULD avoid defining mailboxes where the Local-part requires (or uses) the Quoted-string form".
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The local-part `postmaster` is treated specially—it is case-insensitive, and should be forwarded to the domain email administrator.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Technically all other local-parts are case-sensitive, therefore `janes@example.com` and `JaneS@example.com` specify different mailboxes; however, many organizations treat uppercase and lowercase letters as equivalent.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Indeed, RFC 5321 warns that "a host that expects to receive mail SHOULD avoid defining mailboxes where ... the Local-part is case-sensitive".
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Despite the wide range of special characters that are technically valid, organisations, mail services, mail servers, and mail clients in practice often do not accept all of them.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] For example, Windows Live Hotmail only allows creation of email addresses using alphanumerics, dot (`.`), underscore (`_`) and hyphen (`-`).
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Common advice is to avoid using some special characters to avoid the risk of rejected emails.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] According to RFC 5321 2.3.11 *Mailbox and Address,* "the local-part MUST be interpreted and assigned semantics only by the host specified in the domain of the address".
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] This means that no assumptions can be made about the meaning of the local-part of another mail server.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] It is entirely up to the configuration of the mail server.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Interpretation of the local-part is dependent on the conventions and policies implemented in the mail server.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] For example, case sensitivity may distinguish mailboxes differing only in capitalization of characters of the local-part, although this is not very common.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] For example, Gmail ignores all dots in the local-part of user email address for the purposes of determining account identity.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Some mail services support a tag included in the local-part, such that the address is an alias to a prefix of the local-part.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Typically the characters following a plus and less often the characters following a minus, so fred+bar@domain and fred+foo@domain might end up in the same inbox as fred+@domain or even as fred@domain.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] For example, the address *joeuser+tag@example.com* denotes the same delivery address as *joeuser@example.com*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] RFC 5233 refers to this convention as *subaddressing*, but it is also known as *plus addressing*, *tagged addressing* or *mail extensions*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] This can be useful for tagging emails for sorting, and for spam control.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Addresses of this form, using various separators between the base name and the tag, are supported by several email services, including Andrew Project (plus), Runbox (plus), Gmail (plus), Rackspace (plus), Yahoo!
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Mail Plus (hyphen), Apple's iCloud (plus), Outlook.com (plus), Mailfence (plus), Proton Mail (plus), Fastmail (plus and Subdomain Addressing), postale.io (plus), Pobox (plus), MeMail (plus), and MTAs like MMDF (equals), Qmail and Courier Mail Server (hyphen).
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Postfix and Exim allow configuring an arbitrary separator from the legal character set.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The text of the tag may be used to apply filtering, or to create *single-use*, or disposable email addresses.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] In addition, the domain may be an IP address literal, surrounded by square brackets `[]`, such as `jsmith@[192.168.2.1]` or `jsmith@[IPv6:2001:db8::1]`, although this is rarely seen except in email spam.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Internationalized domain names (which are encoded to comply with the requirements for a hostname) allow for presentation of non-ASCII domains.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] In mail systems compliant with RFC 6531 and RFC 6532, an email address may be encoded as UTF-8, both a local-part as well as a domain name.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Comments are allowed in the domain as well as in the local-part; for example, `jane.smith@(comment)example.com` and `jane.smith@example.com(comment)` are equivalent to `jane.smith@example.com`.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] RFC 2606 specifies that certain domains, for example those intended for documentation and testing, should not be resolvable and that as a result mail addressed to mailboxes in them and their subdomains should be non-deliverable.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Of note for email are *example*, *invalid*, *example.com*, *example.net*, and *example.org*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Email addresses are often requested as input to website as validation of user existence.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Other validation methods are available, such as cell phone number validation, postal mail validation, and fax validation.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] An email address is generally recognized as having two parts joined with an at-sign (*@*), although the technical specifications detailed in RFC 822 and subsequent RFCs are more extensive.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Syntactically correct, verified email addresses do not guarantee that an email box exists.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Thus many email servers use other techniques and check the mailbox existence against relevant systems such as the Domain Name System for the domain or using callback verification to check if the mailbox exists.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Callback verification is an imperfect solution, as it may be disabled to avoid a directory harvest attack, or callbacks may be reported as spam and lead to listing on a DNSBL.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Several validation techniques may be utilized to validate a user email address.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Some companies offer services to validate an email address, often using an application programming interface, but there is no guarantee that it will provide accurate results.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The IETF conducts a technical and standards working group devoted to internationalization issues of email addresses, entitled *Email Address Internationalization* (EAI, also known as IMA, Internationalized Mail Address).
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] This group produced RFC 6530, 6531, 6532 and 6533, and continues to work on additional EAI-related RFCs.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The IETF's EAI Working group published RFC 6530 "Overview and Framework for Internationalized Email" that enabled non-ASCII characters to be used in both the local-parts and domain of an email address.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] RFC 6530 provides for email based on the UTF-8 encoding, which permits the full repertoire of Unicode.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] RFC 6531 provides a mechanism for SMTP servers to negotiate transmission of the SMTPUTF8 content.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The basic EAI concepts involve exchanging mail in UTF-8.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Though the original proposal included a downgrading mechanism for legacy systems, this has now been dropped.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The local servers are responsible for the local-part of the address, whereas the domain would be restricted by the rules of internationalized domain names, though still transmitted in UTF-8.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The mail server is also responsible for any mapping mechanism between the IMA form and any ASCII alias.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] EAI enables users to have a localized address in a native language script or character set, as well as an ASCII form for communicating with legacy systems or for script-independent use.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Applications that recognize internationalized domain names and mail addresses must have facilities to convert these representations.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Significant demand for such addresses is expected in China, Japan, Russia, and other markets that have large user bases in a non-Latin-based writing system.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] For example, in addition to the .in top-level domain, the government of India in 2011 got approval for ".bharat", (from *Bhārat Gaṇarājya*), written in seven different scripts for use by Gujrati, Marathi, Bangali, Tamil, Telugu, Punjabi and Urdu speakers.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] Indian company XgenPlus.com claims to be the world's first EAI mailbox provider, and the Government of Rajasthan now supplies a free email account on domain राजस्थान.भारत for every citizen of the state.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] A leading media house Rajasthan Patrika launched their IDN domain पत्रिका.भारत with contactable email.
[src:nodemailer-email/email-address] The example addresses below would not be handled by RFC 5321-based servers without an extension, but are permitted by the **UTF8SMTP** extension of RFC 6530 and 6531.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email operates across computer networks, primarily the Internet, and also local area networks.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Today's email systems are based on a store-and-forward model.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email servers accept, forward, deliver, and store messages.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Neither the users nor their computers are required to be online simultaneously; they need to connect, typically to a mail server or a webmail interface to send or receive messages or download it.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Originally a text-only ASCII communications medium, Internet email was extended by MIME to carry text in expanded character sets and multimedia content such as images.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] International email, with internationalized email addresses using UTF-8, is standardized but not widely adopted.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The service is often simply referred to as *mail*, and a single piece of electronic mail is called a *message*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The conventions for fields within emails—the "To", "From", "CC", "BCC" etc.—began with RFC-680 in 1975.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] An Internet email consists of an *envelope* and *content*; the content consists of a *header* and a *body*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Computer-based messaging between users of the same system became possible after the advent of time-sharing in the early 1960s, with a notable implementation by MIT's CTSS project in 1965.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Most developers of early mainframes and minicomputers developed similar, but generally incompatible, mail applications.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] In 1971 the first ARPANET network mail was sent, introducing the now-familiar address syntax with the '@' symbol designating the user's system address.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Over a series of RFCs, conventions were refined for sending mail messages over the File Transfer Protocol.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Proprietary electronic mail systems soon began to emerge.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] IBM, CompuServe and Xerox used in-house mail systems in the 1970s; CompuServe sold a commercial intraoffice mail product in 1978 to IBM and to Xerox from 1981.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] DEC's ALL-IN-1 and Hewlett-Packard's HPMAIL (later HP DeskManager) were released in 1982; development work on the former began in the late 1970s and the latter became the world's largest selling email system.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) was implemented on the ARPANET in 1983.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] LAN email systems emerged in the mid-1980s.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] For a time in the late 1980s and early 1990s, it seemed likely that either a proprietary commercial system or the X.400 email system, part of the Government Open Systems Interconnection Profile (GOSIP), would predominate.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] However, once the final restrictions on carrying commercial traffic over the Internet ended in 1995, a combination of factors made the current Internet suite of SMTP, POP3 and IMAP email protocols the standard (see Protocol Wars).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The following is a typical sequence of events that takes place when sender Alice transmits a message using a mail user agent (MUA) addressed to the email address of the recipient.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The MSA determines the destination address provided in the SMTP protocol (not from the message header)—in this case, *bob@b.org*—which is a fully qualified domain address (FQDA).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The part before the @ sign is the *local part* of the address, often the username of the recipient, and the part after the @ sign is a domain name.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The MSA resolves a domain name to determine the fully qualified domain name of the mail server in the Domain Name System (DNS).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The DNS server for the domain *b.org* (*ns.b.org*) responds with any MX records listing the mail exchange servers for that domain, in this case *mx.b.org*, a message transfer agent (MTA) server run by the recipient's ISP.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] 4. smtp.a.org sends the message to mx.b.org using SMTP.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] This server may need to forward the message to other MTAs before the message reaches the final message delivery agent (MDA).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The MDA delivers it to the mailbox of user *bob*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Bob's MUA picks up the message using either the Post Office Protocol (POP3) or the Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Many MTAs used to accept messages for any recipient on the Internet and do their best to deliver them.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Such MTAs are called *open mail relays*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] This was very important in the early days of the Internet when network connections were unreliable.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] However, this mechanism proved to be exploitable by originators of unsolicited bulk email and as a consequence open mail relays have become rare, and many MTAs do not accept messages from open mail relays.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email pre-dates instant messaging, and transmission favors reliability over speed, in order to be able to cope with unreliable network links and busy servers (more common in the early days of the Internet).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Mail can be queued and retried for up to five days before senders are notified of a permanent delivery failure.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Messages are timestamped as they pass through each server, allowing for diagnosis of slow delivery, though analysis is complicated by time zones and computer clocks that are inaccurately set.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email messages classified as spam by a spam filter may be sorted into a separate folder which the recipient must check manually, or may be dropped entirely.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The basic Internet message format used for email is defined by RFC 5322, with encoding of non-ASCII data and multimedia content attachments defined in RFC 2045 through RFC 2049, collectively called *Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions* or *MIME*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The extensions in International email apply only to email.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Earlier, in 2001, RFC 2822 had in turn replaced RFC 822, which had been the standard for Internet email for decades.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Published in 1982, RFC 822 was based on the earlier RFC 733 for the ARPANET.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Internet email messages consist of two sections, "header" and "body".
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The header is structured into fields such as From, To, CC, Subject, Date, and other information about the email.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] In the process of transporting email messages between systems, SMTP communicates delivery parameters and information using message header fields.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The body contains the message, as unstructured text, sometimes containing a signature block at the end.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The header is separated from the body by a blank line.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] RFC 5322 specifies the syntax of the email header.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Each email message has a header (the "header section" of the message, according to the specification), comprising a number of fields ("header fields").
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Each field has a name ("field name" or "header field name"), followed by the separator character ":", and a value ("field body" or "header field body").
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Each field name begins in the first character of a new line in the header section, and begins with a non-whitespace printable character.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] It ends with the separator character ":".
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The separator is followed by the field value (the "field body").
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The value can continue onto subsequent lines if those lines have space or tab as their first character.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Field names and, without SMTPUTF8, field bodies are restricted to 7-bit ASCII characters.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Some non-ASCII values may be represented using MIME encoded words.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email header fields can be multi-line, with each line recommended to be no more than 78 characters, although the limit is 998 characters.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Header fields defined by RFC 5322 contain only US-ASCII characters; for encoding characters in other sets, a syntax specified in RFC 2047 may be used.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] In some examples, the IETF EAI working group defines some standards track extensions, replacing previous experimental extensions so UTF-8 encoded Unicode characters may be used within the header.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] In particular, this allows email addresses to use non-ASCII characters.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Such addresses are supported by Google and Microsoft products, and promoted by some government agents.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] RFC 3864 describes registration procedures for message header fields at the IANA; it provides for permanent and provisional field names, including also fields defined for MIME, netnews, and HTTP, and referencing relevant RFCs.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The *To:* field may be unrelated to the addresses to which the message is delivered.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The delivery list is supplied separately to the transport protocol, SMTP, which may be extracted from the header content.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The "To:" field is similar to the addressing at the top of a conventional letter delivered according to the address on the outer envelope.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] In the same way, the "From:" field may not be the sender.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Some mail servers apply email authentication systems to messages relayed.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Data pertaining to the server's activity is also part of the header, as defined below.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Other fields added on top of the header by the receiving server may be called *trace fields*.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Internet email was designed for 7-bit ASCII.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Most email software is 8-bit clean, but must assume it will communicate with 7-bit servers and mail readers.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The MIME standard introduced character set specifiers and two content transfer encodings to enable transmission of non-ASCII data: quoted printable for mostly 7-bit content with a few characters outside that range and base64 for arbitrary binary data.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The 8BITMIME and BINARY extensions were introduced to allow transmission of mail without the need for these encodings, but many mail transport agents may not support them.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Therefore, for international character sets, Unicode is growing in popularity.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Most modern graphic email clients allow the use of either plain text or HTML for the message body at the option of the user.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] HTML email messages often include an automatic-generated plain text copy for compatibility.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Advantages of HTML include the ability to include in-line links and images, set apart previous messages in block quotes, wrap naturally on any display, use emphasis such as underlines and italics, and change font styles.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Disadvantages include the increased size of the email, privacy concerns about web bugs, abuse of HTML email as a vector for phishing attacks and the spread of malicious software.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Some e-mail clients interpret the body as HTML even in the absence of a `Content-Type: html` header field; this may cause various problems.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Some web-based mailing lists recommend all posts be made in plain text, with 72 or 80 characters per line for all the above reasons, and because they have a significant number of readers using text-based email clients such as Mutt.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Various informal conventions evolved for marking up plain text in email and usenet posts, which later led to the development of formal languages like setext *(c.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] 1992)* and many others, the most popular of them being markdown.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Some Microsoft email clients may allow rich formatting using their proprietary Rich Text Format (RTF), but this should be avoided unless the recipient is guaranteed to have a compatible email client.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Messages are exchanged between hosts using the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol with software programs called mail transfer agents (MTAs); and delivered to a mail store by programs called mail delivery agents (MDAs, also sometimes called local delivery agents, LDAs).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Accepting a message obliges an MTA to deliver it, and when a message cannot be delivered, that MTA must send a bounce message back to the sender, indicating the problem.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Users can retrieve their messages from servers using standard protocols such as POP or IMAP, or, as is more likely in a large corporate environment, with a proprietary protocol specific to Novell Groupwise, Lotus Notes or Microsoft Exchange Servers.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Programs used by users for retrieving, reading, and managing email are called mail user agents (MUAs).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] When opening an email, it is marked as "read", which typically visibly distinguishes it from "unread" messages on clients' user interfaces.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email clients may allow hiding read emails from the inbox so the user can focus on the unread.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Mail can be stored on the client, on the server side, or in both places.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Standard formats for mailboxes include Maildir and mbox.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Several prominent email clients use their own proprietary format and require conversion software to transfer email between them.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Server-side storage is often in a proprietary format but since access is through a standard protocol such as IMAP, moving email from one server to another can be done with any MUA supporting the protocol.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Many current email users do not run MTA, MDA or MUA programs themselves, but use a web-based email platform, such as Gmail or Yahoo!
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Such webmail interfaces allow users to access their mail with any standard web browser, from any computer, rather than relying on a local email client.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Upon reception of email messages, email client applications save messages in operating system files in the file system.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Some clients save individual messages as separate files, while others use various database formats, often proprietary, for collective storage.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] A historical standard of storage is the *mbox* format.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] format, containing the email header and body, including attachments in one or more of several formats.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Some applications (like Apple Mail) leave attachments encoded in messages for searching while also saving separate copies of the attachments.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Others separate attachments from messages and save them in a specific directory.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The URI scheme, as registered with the IANA, defines the `mailto:` scheme for SMTP email addresses.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Though its use is not strictly defined, URLs of this form are intended to be used to open the new message window of the user's mail client when the URL is activated, with the address as defined by the URL in the *To:* field.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Many clients also support query string parameters for the other email fields, such as its subject line or carbon copy recipients.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Many email providers have a web-based email client.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] This allows users to log into the email account by using any compatible web browser to send and receive their email.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Mail is typically not downloaded to the web client, so it cannot be read without a current Internet connection.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The Post Office Protocol 3 (POP3) is a mail access protocol used by a client application to read messages from the mail server.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Received messages are often deleted from the server.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] POP supports simple download-and-delete requirements for access to remote mailboxes (termed maildrop in the POP RFC's).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] POP3 allows downloading messages on a local computer and reading them even when offline.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) provides features to manage a mailbox from multiple devices.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Small portable devices like smartphones are increasingly used to check email while traveling and to make brief replies, larger devices with better keyboard access being used to reply at greater length.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] IMAP shows the headers of messages, the sender and the subject and the device needs to request to download specific messages.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Usually, the mail is left in folders in the mail server.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email has been widely accepted by businesses, governments and non-governmental organizations in the developed world, and it is one of the key parts of an 'e-revolution' in workplace communication (with the other key plank being widespread adoption of highspeed Internet).
[src:nodemailer-email/email] A sponsored 2010 study on workplace communication found 83% of U.S. knowledge workers felt email was critical to their success and productivity at work.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] can be inconvenient, time-consuming, and costly.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email provides a method of exchanging information between two or more people with no set-up costs and that is generally far less expensive than a physical meeting or phone call.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] communication by meetings or phone calls, participants must work on the same schedule, and each participant must spend the same amount of time in the meeting or call.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] : each participant may control their schedule independently.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Batch processing of incoming emails can improve workflow compared to interrupting calls.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Much faster than most of the alternatives.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Unlike a telephone or in-person conversation, email by its nature creates a detailed written record of the communication, the identity of the sender(s) and recipient(s) and the date and time the message was sent.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] , saved emails can be used to prove that an individual was advised of certain issues, as each email has the date and time recorded on it.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] As well pre-processing of customer's orders or addressing the person in charge can be realized by automated procedures.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email marketing via "opt-in" is often successfully used to send special sales offerings and new product information.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Depending on the recipient's culture, email sent without permission—such as an "opt-in"—is likely to be viewed as unwelcome "email spam".
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Many users access their personal emails from friends and family members using a personal computer in their house or apartment.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email has become used on smartphones and on all types of computers.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Mobile "apps" for email increase accessibility to the medium for users who are out of their homes.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] While in the earliest years of email, users could only access email on desktop computers, in the 2010s, it is possible for users to check their email when they are away from home, whether they are across town or across the world.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Alerts can also be sent to the smartphone or other devices to notify them immediately of new messages.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] This has given email the ability to be used for more frequent communication between users and allowed them to check their email and write messages throughout the day.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] As of 2011, there were approximately 1.4 billion email users worldwide and 50 billion non-spam emails that were sent daily.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Individuals often check emails on smartphones for both personal and work-related messages.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] It was found that US adults check their email more than they browse the web or check their Facebook accounts, making email the most popular activity for users to do on their smartphones.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] 78% of the respondents in the study revealed that they check their email on their phone.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] It was also found that 30% of consumers use only their smartphone to check their email, and 91% were likely to check their email at least once per day on their smartphone.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] However, the percentage of consumers using email on a smartphone ranges and differs dramatically across different countries.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] For example, in comparison to 75% of those consumers in the US who used it, only 17% in India did.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] As of 2010, the number of Americans visiting email web sites had fallen 6 percent after peaking in November 2009.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] For persons 12 to 17, the number was down 18 percent.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Young people preferred instant messaging, texting and social media.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Technology writer Matt Richtel said in *The New York Times* that email was like the VCR, vinyl records and film cameras—no longer cool and something older people do.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] A 2015 survey of Android users showed that persons 13 to 24 used messaging apps 3.5 times as much as those over 45, and were far less likely to use email.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email messages may have one or more attachments, which are additional files that are appended to the email.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Typical attachments include Microsoft Word documents, PDF documents, and scanned images of paper documents.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] In principle, there is no technical restriction on the size or number of attachments.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] However, in practice, email clients, servers, and Internet service providers implement various limitations on the size of files, or complete email – typically to 25MB or less.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Furthermore, due to technical reasons, attachment sizes as seen by these transport systems can differ from what the user sees, which can be confusing to senders when trying to assess whether they can safely send a file by email.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Where larger files need to be shared, various file hosting services are available and commonly used.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The ubiquity of email for knowledge workers and "white collar" employees has led to concerns that recipients face an "information overload" in dealing with increasing volumes of email.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] With the growth in mobile devices, by default employees may also receive work-related emails outside of their working day.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] This can lead to increased stress and decreased satisfaction with work.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Some observers even argue it could have a significant negative economic effect, as efforts to read the many emails could reduce productivity.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The low cost of sending such email meant that, by 2003, up to 30% of total email traffic was spam, and was threatening the usefulness of email as a practical tool.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] In September 2017, for example, the proportion of spam to legitimate email rose to 59.56%.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The percentage of spam email in 2021 is estimated to be 85%.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Emails are a major vector for the distribution of malware.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] This is often achieved by attaching malicious programs to the message and persuading potential victims to open the file.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Types of malware distributed via email include computer worms and ransomware.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email spoofing occurs when the email message header is designed to make the message appear to come from a known or trusted source.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email spam and phishing methods typically use spoofing to mislead the recipient about the true message origin.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email spoofing may be done as a prank, or as part of a criminal effort to defraud an individual or organization.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] An example of a potentially fraudulent email spoofing is if an individual creates an email that appears to be an invoice from a major company, and then sends it to one or more recipients.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] In some cases, these fraudulent emails incorporate the logo of the purported organization and even the email address may appear legitimate.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Email bombing is the intentional sending of large volumes of messages to a target address.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The overloading of the target email address can render it unusable and can even cause the mail server to crash.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Today it can be important to distinguish between the Internet and internal email systems.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Internet email may travel and be stored on networks and computers without the sender's or the recipient's control.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] During the transit time it is possible that third parties read or even modify the content.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Internal mail systems, in which the information never leaves the organizational network, may be more secure, although information technology personnel and others whose function may involve monitoring or managing may be accessing the email of other employees.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] There are cryptography applications that can serve as a remedy to one or more of the above.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Additionally, many mail user agents do not protect logins and passwords, making them easy to intercept by an attacker.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Encrypted authentication schemes such as SASL prevent this.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Finally, the attached files share many of the same hazards as those found in peer-to-peer filesharing.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Attached files may contain trojans or viruses.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] It is possible for an exchange of emails to form a binding contract, so users must be careful about what they send through email correspondence.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] A signature block on an email may be interpreted as satisfying a signature requirement for a contract.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Flaming occurs when a person sends a message (or many messages) with angry or antagonistic content.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The term is derived from the use of the word *incendiary* to describe particularly heated email discussions.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The ease and impersonality of email communications mean that the social norms that encourage civility in person or via telephone do not exist and civility may be forgotten.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Also known as "email fatigue", email bankruptcy is when a user ignores a large number of email messages after falling behind in reading and answering them.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The reason for falling behind is often due to information overload and a general sense there is so much information that it is not possible to read it all.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] As a solution, people occasionally send a "boilerplate" message explaining that their email inbox is full, and that they are in the process of clearing out all the messages.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Harvard University law professor Lawrence Lessig is credited with coining this term, but he may only have popularized it.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Originally Internet email was completely ASCII text-based.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] MIME now allows body content text and some header content text in international character sets, but other headers and email addresses using UTF-8, while standardized have yet to be widely adopted.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] The original SMTP mail service provides limited mechanisms for tracking a transmitted message, and none for verifying that it has been delivered or read.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] It requires that each mail server must either deliver it onward or return a failure notice (bounce message), but both software bugs and system failures can cause messages to be lost.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] To remedy this, the IETF introduced Delivery Status Notifications (delivery receipts) and Message Disposition Notifications (return receipts); however, these are not universally deployed in production.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] In the absence of standard methods, a range of system based around the use of web bugs have been developed.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] However, these are often seen as underhand or raising privacy concerns, and only work with email clients that support rendering of HTML.
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Many mail clients now default to not showing "web content".
[src:nodemailer-email/email] Webmail providers can also disrupt web bugs by pre-caching images.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The **`Promise`** object represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] To learn about the way promises work and how you can use them, we advise you to read Using promises first.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] A `Promise` is a proxy for a value not necessarily known when the promise is created.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] It allows you to associate handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual success value or failure reason.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This lets asynchronous methods return values like synchronous methods: instead of immediately returning the final value, the asynchronous method returns a *promise* to supply the value at some point in the future.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The *eventual state* of a pending promise can either be *fulfilled* with a value or *rejected* with a reason (error).
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] When either of these options occur, the associated handlers queued up by a promise's `then` method are called.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] If the promise has already been fulfilled or rejected when a corresponding handler is attached, the handler will be called, so there is no race condition between an asynchronous operation completing and its handlers being attached.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] A promise is said to be *settled* if it is either fulfilled or rejected, but not pending.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] (Flowchart showing how the Promise state transitions between pending, fulfilled, and rejected via then/catch handlers.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] A pending promise can become either fulfilled or rejected.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] If fulfilled, the "on fulfillment" handler, or first parameter of the then() method, is executed and carries out further asynchronous actions.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] You will also hear the term *resolved* used with promises — this means that the promise is settled or "locked-in" to match the eventual state of another promise, and further resolving or rejecting it has no effect.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The States and fates document from the original Promise proposal contains more details about promise terminology.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Colloquially, "resolved" promises are often equivalent to "fulfilled" promises, but as illustrated in "States and fates", resolved promises can be pending or rejected as well.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This promise is already *resolved* at the time when it's created (because the `resolveOuter` is called synchronously), but it is resolved with another promise, and therefore won't be *fulfilled* until 1 second later, when the inner promise fulfills.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] In practice, the "resolution" is often done behind the scenes and not observable, and only its fulfillment or rejection are.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] `Promise` itself has no first-class protocol for cancellation, but you may be able to directly cancel the underlying asynchronous operation, typically using `AbortController`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The promise methods `then()`, `catch()`, and `finally()` are used to associate further action with a promise that becomes settled.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method takes up to two arguments; the first argument is a callback function for the fulfilled case of the promise, and the second argument is a callback function for the rejected case.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The `catch()` and `finally()` methods call `then()` internally and make error handling less verbose.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] For example, a `catch()` is really just a `then()` without passing the fulfillment handler.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] As these methods return promises, they can be chained.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] We will use the following terminology: *initial promise* is the promise on which `then` is called; *new promise* is the promise returned by `then`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The two callbacks passed to `then` are called *fulfillment handler* and *rejection handler*, respectively.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The settled state of the initial promise determines which handler to execute.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The completion of the handler determines the settled state of the new promise.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] For example, in the code above, if `myPromise` rejects, `handleRejectedA` will be called, and if `handleRejectedA` completes normally (without throwing or returning a rejected promise), the promise returned by the first `then` will be fulfilled instead of staying rejected.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Therefore, if an error must be handled immediately, but we want to maintain the error state down the chain, we must throw an error of some type in the rejection handler.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] On the other hand, in the absence of an immediate need, we can leave out error handling until the final `catch()` handler.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Each time, JavaScript picks a job from the queue and executes it to completion.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The jobs are defined by the executor of the `Promise()` constructor, the handlers passed to `then`, or any platform API that returns a promise.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The promises in a chain represent the dependency relationship between these jobs.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] When a promise settles, the respective handlers associated with it are added to the back of the job queue.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] A promise can participate in more than one chain.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] For the following code, the fulfillment of `promiseA` will cause both `handleFulfilled1` and `handleFulfilled2` to be added to the job queue.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Because `handleFulfilled1` is registered first, it will be invoked first.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] An action can be assigned to an already settled promise.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] In this case, the action is added immediately to the back of the job queue and will be performed when all existing jobs are completed.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Therefore, an action for an already "settled" promise will occur only after the current synchronous code completes and at least one loop-tick has passed.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This guarantees that promise actions are asynchronous.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The JavaScript ecosystem had made multiple Promise implementations long before it became part of the language.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Despite being represented differently internally, at the minimum, all Promise-like objects implement the *Thenable* interface.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] A thenable implements the `.then()` method, which is called with two callbacks: one for when the promise is fulfilled, one for when it's rejected.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] To interoperate with the existing Promise implementations, the language allows using thenables in place of promises.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] For example, `Promise.resolve` will not only resolve promises, but also trace thenables.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method is responsible for scheduling the execution of the provided `onFulfilled` and `onRejected` callbacks.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Its semantics, including error handling and asynchronicity, are precisely defined in the Promises/A+ specification, and we shall not repeat them here.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] It's very rare that you need to implement a thenable yourself; even if you are not using native promises, you would probably be using a Promise library such as Bluebird.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Fulfills when **all** of the promises fulfill; rejects when **any** of the promises rejects.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Fulfills when **any** of the promises fulfills; rejects when **all** of the promises reject.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Settles when **any** of the promises settles.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] In other words, fulfills when any of the promises fulfills; rejects when any of the promises rejects.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] All these methods take an iterable of promises (thenables, to be exact) and return a new promise.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] They all support subclassing, which means they can be called on subclasses of `Promise`, and the result will be a promise of the subclass type.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] To do so, the subclass's constructor must implement the same signature as the `Promise()` constructor — accepting a single `executor` function that can be called with the `resolve` and `reject` callbacks as parameters.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The subclass must also have a `resolve` static method that can be called like `Promise.resolve()` to resolve values to promises.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Note that JavaScript is single-threaded by nature, so at a given instant, only one task will be executing, although control can shift between different promises, making execution of the promises appear concurrent.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Parallel execution in JavaScript can only be achieved through worker threads.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The constructor is primarily used to wrap functions that do not already support promises.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Returns the constructor used to construct return values from promise methods.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Takes an iterable of promises as input and returns a single `Promise`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This returned promise fulfills when all of the input's promises fulfill (including when an empty iterable is passed), with an array of the fulfillment values.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] It rejects when any of the input's promises reject, with this first rejection reason.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This returned promise fulfills when all of the input's promises settle (including when an empty iterable is passed), with an array of objects that describe the outcome of each promise.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This returned promise fulfills when any of the input's promises fulfill, with this first fulfillment value.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] It rejects when all of the input's promises reject (including when an empty iterable is passed), with an `AggregateError` containing an array of rejection reasons.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This returned promise settles with the eventual state of the first promise that settles.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Returns a new `Promise` object that is rejected with the given reason.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Returns a `Promise` object that is resolved with the given value.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] If the value is a thenable (i.e., has a `then` method), the returned promise will "follow" that thenable, adopting its eventual state; otherwise, the returned promise will be fulfilled with the value.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Takes a callback of any kind (returns or throws, synchronously or asynchronously) and wraps its result in a `Promise`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Returns an object containing a new `Promise` object and two functions to resolve or reject it, corresponding to the two parameters passed to the executor of the `Promise()` constructor.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] These properties are defined on `Promise.prototype` and shared by all `Promise` instances.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The constructor function that created the instance object.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] For `Promise` instances, the initial value is the `Promise` constructor.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Promise"`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Appends a rejection handler callback to the promise, and returns a new promise resolving to the return value of the callback if it is called, or to its original fulfillment value if the promise is instead fulfilled.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Appends a handler to the promise, and returns a new promise that is resolved when the original promise is resolved.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The handler is called when the promise is settled, whether fulfilled or rejected.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Appends fulfillment and rejection handlers to the promise, and returns a new promise resolving to the return value of the called handler, or to its original settled value if the promise was not handled (i.e., if the relevant handler `onFulfilled` or `onRejected` is not a function).
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] In this example, we use `setTimeout(...)` to simulate async code.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] In reality, you will probably be using something like XHR or an HTML API.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This example shows diverse techniques for using Promise capabilities and diverse situations that can occur.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] To understand this, start by scrolling to the bottom of the code block, and examine the promise chain.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Upon provision of an initial promise, a chain of promises can follow.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The chain is composed of `.then()` calls, and typically (but not necessarily) has a single `.catch()` at the end, optionally followed by `.finally()`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] In this example, the promise chain is initiated by a custom-written `new Promise()` construct; but in actual practice, promise chains more typically start with an API function (written by someone else) that returns a promise.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The example function `tetheredGetNumber()` shows that a promise generator will utilize `reject()` while setting up an asynchronous call, or within the call-back, or both.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The function `promiseGetWord()` illustrates how an API function might generate and return a promise in a self-contained manner.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Note that the function `troubleWithGetNumber()` ends with a `throw`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] That is forced because a promise chain goes through all the `.then()` promises, even after an error, and without the `throw`, the error would seem "fixed".
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This is a hassle, and for this reason, it is common to omit `onRejected` throughout the chain of `.then()` promises, and just have a single `onRejected` in the final `catch()`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Comprehension is enhanced by seeing the errors actually occur.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] To force more errors, change the `threshold` values.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This small example shows the mechanism of a `Promise`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The `testPromise()` method is called each time the `<button>` is clicked.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] It creates a promise that will be fulfilled, using `setTimeout()`, to the promise count (number starting from 1) every 1-3 seconds, at random.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The `Promise()` constructor is used to create the promise.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The fulfillment of the promise is logged, via a fulfill callback set using `p1.then()`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] A few logs show how the synchronous part of the method is decoupled from the asynchronous completion of the promise.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] By clicking the button several times in a short amount of time, you'll even see the different promises being fulfilled one after another.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Another example using `Promise` and `XMLHttpRequest` to load an image is shown below.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Each step is commented on and allows you to follow the Promise and XHR architecture closely.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] A settings object is an environment that provides additional information when JavaScript code is running.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This includes the realm and module map, as well as HTML specific information such as the origin.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] The incumbent settings object is tracked in order to ensure that the browser knows which one to use for a given piece of user code.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] To better picture this, we can take a closer look at how the realm might be an issue.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] A **realm** can be roughly thought of as the global object.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] What is unique about realms is that they hold all of the necessary information to run JavaScript code.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This includes objects like `Array` and `Error`.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] Each settings object has its own "copy" of these and they are not shared.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] That can cause some unexpected behavior in relation to promises.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] In order to get around this, we track something called the **incumbent settings object**.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This represents information specific to the context of the user code responsible for a certain function call.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] To illustrate this a bit further we can take a look at how an `<iframe>` embedded in a document communicates with its host.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] In the above example, the inner text of the `<iframe>` will be updated only if the incumbent settings object is tracked.
[src:nodemailer-email/global-objects-promise] This is because without tracking the incumbent, we may end up using the wrong environment to send the message.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] See nodemailer.com for documentation and terms.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Check out **EmailEngine** – a self-hosted email gateway that allows making **REST requests against IMAP and SMTP servers**.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] EmailEngine also sends webhooks whenever something changes on the registered accounts.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Using the email accounts registered with EmailEngine, you can receive and send emails.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] EmailEngine supports OAuth2, delayed sends, opens and clicks tracking, bounce detection, etc.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] All on top of regular email accounts without an external MTA service.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Documentation for Nodemailer can be found at nodemailer.com.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] You are using an older Node.js version than v6.0.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Upgrade Node.js to get support for the spread operator.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Nodemailer supports all Node.js versions starting from Node.js@v6.0.0.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Gmail either works well, or it does not work at all.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] It is probably easier to switch to an alternative service instead of fixing issues with Gmail.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] If Gmail does not work for you, then don't use it.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Timeout usually occurs when you try to open a connection to a firewalled port either on the server or on your machine.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Some ISPs also block email ports to prevent spamming.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] It's either a firewall issue, or your SMTP server blocks authentication attempts from some servers.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Node.js uses c-ares to resolve domain names, not the DNS library provided by the system, so if you have some custom DNS routing set up, it might be ignored.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Nodemailer runs dns.resolve4() and dns.resolve6() to resolve hostname into an IP address.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] If both calls fail, then Nodemailer will fall back to dns.lookup().
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] If this does not work for you, you can hard code the IP address into the configuration like shown below.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] In that case, Nodemailer would not perform any DNS lookups.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] Nodemailer has official support for Node.js only.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] For anything related to TypeScript, you need to directly contact the authors of the type definitions.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] If you are having issues with Nodemailer, then the best way to find help would be Stack Overflow or revisit the docs.
[src:nodemailer-email/nodemailer-nodemailer] The Nodemailer logo was designed by Sven Kristjansen.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The **Simple Mail Transfer Protocol** (**SMTP**) is an Internet standard communication protocol for electronic mail transmission.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Mail servers and other message transfer agents use SMTP to send and receive mail messages.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] User-level email clients typically use SMTP only for sending messages to a mail server for relaying, and typically submit outgoing email to the mail server on port 465 or 587 per RFC 8314.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] For retrieving messages, IMAP and POP are widely used, but proprietary servers also often implement proprietary protocols, e.g., Exchange ActiveSync.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] SMTP's origins began in 1980, building on concepts implemented on the ARPANET since 1971.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] It has been updated, modified and extended multiple times.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The protocol version in common use today has extensible structure with various extensions for authentication, encryption, binary data transfer, and internationalized email addresses.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] SMTP servers commonly use the Transmission Control Protocol on port number 25 (between servers) and 587 (for submission from authenticated clients), both with or without encryption, and 465 with encryption for submission.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Various forms of one-to-one electronic messaging were used in the 1960s.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Users communicated using systems developed for specific mainframe computers.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] As more computers were interconnected, especially in the U.S.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Government's ARPANET, standards were developed to permit exchange of messages between different operating systems.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Mail on the ARPANET traces its roots to 1971: the Mail Box Protocol, which was not implemented, but is discussed in RFC 196; and the SNDMSG program, which Ray Tomlinson of BBN adapted that year to send messages across two computers on the ARPANET.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A further proposal for a Mail Protocol was made in RFC 524 in June 1973, which was not implemented.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The use of the File Transfer Protocol (FTP) for "network mail" on the ARPANET was proposed in RFC 469 in March 1973.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Through RFC 561, RFC 680, RFC 724, and finally RFC 733 in November 1977, a standardized framework for "electronic mail" using FTP mail servers on was developed.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] SMTP grew out of these standards developed during the 1970s.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Ray Tomlinson discussed network mail among the International Network Working Group in *INWG Protocol note 2*, written in September 1974.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] INWG discussed protocols for electronic mail in 1979, which was referenced by Jon Postel in his early work on Internet email.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Postel first proposed an Internet Message Protocol in 1979 as part of the Internet Experiment Note (IEN) series.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In 1980, Postel and Suzanne Sluizer published RFC 772 which proposed the Mail Transfer Protocol as a replacement for the use of the FTP for mail.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] RFC 780 of May 1981 removed all references to FTP and allocated port 57 for TCP and UDP, an allocation that has since been removed by IANA.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In November 1981, Postel published RFC 788 "Simple Mail Transfer Protocol".
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The SMTP standard was developed around the same time as Usenet, a one-to-many communication network with some similarities.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] SMTP became widely used in the early 1980s.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] At the time, it was a complement to the Unix to Unix Copy Program (UUCP), which was better suited for handling email transfers between machines that were intermittently connected.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] SMTP, on the other hand, works best when both the sending and receiving machines are connected to the network all the time.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Both used a store and forward mechanism and are examples of push technology.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Though Usenet's newsgroups were still propagated with UUCP between servers, UUCP as a mail transport has virtually disappeared along with the "bang paths" it used as message routing headers.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Sendmail, released with 4.1cBSD in 1983, was one of the first mail transfer agents (MTA) to implement SMTP.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Over time, as BSD Unix became the most popular operating system on the Internet, Sendmail became the most common mail transfer agent.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The original SMTP protocol supported only unauthenticated unencrypted 7-bit ASCII text communications, susceptible to trivial man-in-the-middle attack, spoofing, and spamming, and requiring any binary data to be encoded to readable text before transmission.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Due to absence of a proper authentication mechanism, by design every SMTP server was an open mail relay.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The Internet Mail Consortium (IMC) reported that 55% of mail servers were open relays in 1998, but less than 1% in 2002.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Because of spam concerns most email providers blocklist open relays, making original SMTP essentially impractical for general use on the Internet.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In November 1995, RFC 1869 defined Extended Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (ESMTP), which established a general structure for all existing and future extensions which aimed to add-in the features missing from the original SMTP.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] ESMTP defines consistent and manageable means by which ESMTP clients and servers can be identified and servers can indicate supported extensions.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Message submission (RFC 2476) and SMTP-AUTH (RFC 2554) were introduced in 1998 and 1999, both describing new trends in email delivery.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Originally, SMTP servers were typically internal to an organization, receiving mail for the organization *from the outside*, and relaying messages from the organization *to the outside*.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] But as time went on, SMTP servers (mail transfer agents), in practice, were expanding their roles to become message submission agents for mail user agents, some of which were now relaying mail *from the outside* of an organization.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Work on message submission (RFC 2476) was originally started because popular mail servers would often rewrite mail in an attempt to fix problems in it, for example, adding a domain name to an unqualified address.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This behavior is helpful when the message being fixed is an initial submission, but dangerous and harmful when the message originated elsewhere and is being relayed.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Cleanly separating mail into submission and relay was seen as a way to permit and encourage rewriting submissions while prohibiting rewriting relay.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] As spam became more prevalent, it was also seen as a way to provide authorization for mail being sent out from an organization, as well as traceability.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This separation of relay and submission quickly became a foundation for modern email security practices.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] As this protocol started out purely ASCII text-based, it did not deal well with binary files, or characters in many non-English languages.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Standards such as Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions (MIME) were developed to encode binary files for transfer through SMTP.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Mail transfer agents (MTAs) developed after Sendmail also tended to be implemented 8-bit clean, so that the alternate "just send eight" strategy could be used to transmit arbitrary text data (in any 8-bit ASCII-like character encoding) via SMTP.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Mojibake was still a problem due to differing character set mappings between vendors, although the email addresses themselves still allowed only ASCII.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] 8-bit-clean MTAs today tend to support the 8BITMIME extension, permitting some binary files to be transmitted almost as easily as plain text (limits on line length and permitted octet values still apply, so that MIME encoding is needed for most non-text data and some text formats).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In 2012, the `SMTPUTF8` extension was created to support UTF-8 text, allowing international content and addresses in non-Latin scripts like Cyrillic or Chinese.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Many people contributed to the core SMTP specifications, among them Jon Postel, Eric Allman, Dave Crocker, Ned Freed, Randall Gellens, John Klensin, and Keith Moore.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Email is submitted by a mail client (mail user agent, MUA) to a mail server (mail submission agent, MSA) using SMTP on TCP port 465 or 587.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Most mailbox providers still allow submission on traditional port 25.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The MSA delivers the mail to its mail transfer agent (MTA).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Often, these two agents are instances of the same software launched with different options on the same machine.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Each process is an MTA (an SMTP server) in its own right.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The boundary MTA uses DNS to look up the MX (mail exchanger) record for the recipient's domain (the part of the email address on the right of `@`).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The MX record contains the name of the target MTA.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Based on the target host and other factors, the sending MTA selects a recipient server and connects to it to complete the mail exchange.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Message transfer can occur in a single connection between two MTAs, or in a series of hops through intermediary systems.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A receiving SMTP server may be the ultimate destination, an intermediate "relay" (that is, it stores and forwards the message) or a "gateway" (that is, it may forward the message using some protocol other than SMTP).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Per RFC 5321 section 2.1, each hop is a formal handoff of responsibility for the message, whereby the receiving server must either deliver the message or properly report the failure to do so.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Once the final hop accepts the incoming message, it hands it to a mail delivery agent (MDA) for local delivery.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] An MDA saves messages in the relevant mailbox format.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] As with sending, this reception can be done using one or multiple computers, but in the diagram above the MDA is depicted as one box near the mail exchanger box.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] An MDA may deliver messages directly to storage, or forward them over a network using SMTP or other protocol such as Local Mail Transfer Protocol (LMTP), a derivative of SMTP designed for this purpose.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Once delivered to the local mail server, the mail is stored for batch retrieval by authenticated mail clients (MUAs).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Webmail clients may use either method, but the retrieval protocol is often not a formal standard.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] SMTP defines message *transport*, not the message *content*.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Thus, it defines the mail *envelope* and its parameters, such as the envelope sender, but not the header (except *trace information*) nor the body of the message itself.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] STD 10 and RFC 5321 define SMTP (the envelope), while STD 11 and RFC 5322 define the message (header and body), formally referred to as the Internet Message Format.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] SMTP is a connection-oriented, text-based protocol in which a mail sender communicates with a mail receiver by issuing command strings and supplying necessary data over a reliable ordered data stream channel, typically a Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) connection.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] An *SMTP session* consists of commands originated by an SMTP client (the initiating agent, sender, or transmitter) and corresponding responses from the SMTP server (the listening agent, or receiver) so that the session is opened, and session parameters are exchanged.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A session may include zero or more SMTP transactions.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] **RCPT** command, to establish a recipient of the message.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This command can be issued multiple times, one for each recipient.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] These addresses are also part of the envelope.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] **DATA** to signal the beginning of the *message text*; the content of the message, as opposed to its envelope.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] It consists of a *message header* and a *message body* separated by an empty line.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] DATA is actually a group of commands, and the server replies twice: once to the *DATA command* itself, to acknowledge that it is ready to receive the text, and the second time after the end-of-data sequence, to either accept or reject the entire message.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Besides the intermediate reply for DATA, each server's reply can be either positive (2xx reply codes) or negative.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Negative replies can be permanent (5xx codes) or transient (4xx codes).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A **reject** is a permanent failure and the client should send a bounce message to the server it received it from.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A **drop** is a positive response followed by message discard rather than delivery.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The initiating host, the SMTP client, can be either an end-user's email client, functionally identified as a mail user agent (MUA), or a relay server's mail transfer agent (MTA), that is an SMTP server acting as an SMTP client, in the relevant session, in order to relay mail.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Fully capable SMTP servers maintain queues of messages for retrying message transmissions that resulted in transient failures.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A MUA knows the *outgoing mail* SMTP server from its configuration.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A relay server typically determines which server to connect to by looking up the MX (Mail eXchange) DNS resource record for each recipient's domain name.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] If no MX record is found, a conformant relaying server (not all are) instead looks up the A record.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Relay servers can also be configured to use a smart host.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A relay server initiates a TCP connection to the server on the "well-known port" for SMTP: port 25, or for connecting to an MSA, port 465 or 587.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The main difference between an MTA and an MSA is that connecting to an MSA requires SMTP Authentication.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In normal use, mail is "pushed" to a destination mail server (or next-hop mail server) as it arrives.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Mail is routed based on the destination server, not the individual user(s) to which it is addressed.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Other protocols, such as the Post Office Protocol (POP) and the Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) are specifically designed for use by individual users retrieving messages and managing mailboxes.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] To permit an intermittently-connected mail server to *pull* messages from a remote server on demand, SMTP has a feature to initiate mail queue processing on a remote server (see Remote Message Queue Starting below).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] POP and IMAP are unsuitable protocols for relaying mail by intermittently-connected machines; they are designed to operate after final delivery, when information critical to the correct operation of mail relay (the "mail envelope") has been removed.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Remote Message Queue Starting enables a remote host to start processing of the mail queue on a server so it may receive messages destined to it by sending a corresponding command.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The original `TURN` command was deemed insecure and was extended in RFC 1985 with the `ETRN` command which operates more securely using an authentication method based on Domain Name System information.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] An email client needs to know the IP address of its initial SMTP server and this has to be given as part of its configuration (usually given as a DNS name).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This server will deliver outgoing messages on behalf of the user.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Server administrators need to impose some control on which clients can use the server.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This enables them to deal with abuse, for example spam.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Under this system, an Internet service provider's (ISP's) SMTP server will not allow access by users who are outside the ISP's network.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] More precisely, the server may only allow access to users with an IP address provided by the ISP, which is equivalent to requiring that they are connected to the Internet using that same ISP.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A mobile user may often be on a network other than that of their normal ISP, and will then find that sending email fails because the configured SMTP server choice is no longer accessible.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] For example, an organisation's SMTP server may only provide service to users on the same network, enforcing this by firewalling to block access by users on the wider Internet.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Or the server may perform range checks on the client's IP address.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] These methods were typically used by corporations and institutions such as universities which provided an SMTP server for outbound mail only for use internally within the organisation.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] However, most of these bodies now use client authentication methods, as described below.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Where a user is mobile, and may use different ISPs to connect to the internet, this kind of usage restriction is onerous, and altering the configured outbound email SMTP server address is impractical.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] It is highly desirable to be able to use email client configuration information that does not need to change.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Modern SMTP servers typically require authentication of clients by credentials before allowing access, rather than restricting access by location as described earlier.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This more flexible system is friendly to mobile users and allows them to have a fixed choice of configured outbound SMTP server.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] SMTP Authentication, often abbreviated SMTP AUTH, is an extension of the SMTP in order to log in using an authentication mechanism.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Communication between mail servers generally uses the standard TCP port 25 designated for SMTP.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Mail *clients* however generally don't use this, instead using specific "submission" ports.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Port 2525 and others may be used by some individual providers, but have never been officially supported.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Many Internet service providers now block all outgoing port 25 traffic from their customers.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Mainly as an anti-spam measure, but also to cure for the higher cost they have when leaving it open.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A typical example of sending a message via SMTP to two mailboxes (*alice* and *theboss*) located in the same mail domain (*example.com*) is reproduced in the following session exchange.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] After the message sender (SMTP client) establishes a reliable communications channel to the message receiver (SMTP server), the session is opened with a greeting by the server, usually containing its fully qualified domain name (FQDN), in this case *smtp.example.com*.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The client initiates its dialog by responding with a `HELO` command identifying itself in the command's parameter with its FQDN (or an address literal if none is available).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The client notifies the receiver of the originating email address of the message in a `MAIL FROM` command.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This is also the return or bounce address in case the message cannot be delivered.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In this example the email message is sent to two mailboxes on the same SMTP server: one for each recipient listed in the `To:` and `Cc:` header fields.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The corresponding SMTP command is `RCPT TO`.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Each successful reception and execution of a command is acknowledged by the server with a result code and response message (e.g., `250 Ok`).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The transmission of the body of the mail message is initiated with a `DATA` command after which it is transmitted verbatim line by line and is terminated with an end-of-data sequence.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This sequence consists of a new-line (`<CR><LF>`), a single full stop (`.`), followed by another new-line (`<CR><LF>`).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Since a message body can contain a line with just a period as part of the text, the client sends *two* periods every time a line starts with a period; correspondingly, the server replaces every sequence of two periods at the beginning of a line with a single one.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Such escaping method is called *dot-stuffing*.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The server's positive reply to the end-of-data, as exemplified, implies that the server has taken the responsibility of delivering the message.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A message can be doubled if there is a communication failure at this time, e.g. due to a power outage: Until the sender has received that `250 Ok` reply, it must assume the message was not delivered.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] On the other hand, after the receiver has decided to accept the message, it must assume the message has been delivered to it.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Thus, during this time span, both agents have active copies of the message that they will try to deliver.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The probability that a communication failure occurs exactly at this step is directly proportional to the amount of filtering that the server performs on the message body, most often for anti-spam purposes.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The limiting timeout is specified to be 10 minutes.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] If the email has other recipients located elsewhere, the client would `QUIT` and connect to an appropriate SMTP server for subsequent recipients after the current destination(s) had been queued.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The information that the client sends in the `HELO` and `MAIL FROM` commands are added (not seen in example code) as additional header fields to the message by the receiving server.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] It adds a `Received` and `Return-Path` header field, respectively.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Some clients are implemented to close the connection after the message is accepted (`250 Ok: queued as 12345`), so the last two lines may actually be omitted.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This causes an error on the server when trying to send the `221 Bye` reply.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Clients learn a server's supported options by using the `EHLO` greeting, as exemplified below, instead of the original `HELO`.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Clients fall back to `HELO` only if the server does not support `EHLO` greeting.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Modern clients may use the ESMTP extension keyword `SIZE` to query the server for the maximum message size that will be accepted.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Older clients and servers may try to transfer excessively sized messages that will be rejected after consuming network resources, including connect time to network links that is paid by the minute.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Users can manually determine in advance the maximum size accepted by ESMTP servers.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The client replaces the `HELO` command with the `EHLO` command.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Thus *smtp2.example.com* declares that it can accept a fixed maximum message size no larger than 14,680,064 octets (8-bit bytes).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In the simplest case, an ESMTP server declares a maximum `SIZE` immediately after receiving an `EHLO`.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] According to RFC 1870, however, the numeric parameter to the `SIZE` extension in the `EHLO` response is optional.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Clients may instead, when issuing a `MAIL FROM` command, include a numeric estimate of the size of the message they are transferring, so that the server can refuse receipt of overly-large messages.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Original SMTP supports only a single body of ASCII text, therefore any binary data needs to be encoded as text into that body of the message before transfer, and then decoded by the recipient.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Binary-to-text encodings, such as uuencode and BinHex were typically used.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The 8BITMIME command was developed to address this.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] It was standardized in 1994 as RFC 1652 It facilitates the transparent exchange of e-mail messages containing octets outside the seven-bit ASCII character set by encoding them as MIME content parts, typically encoded with Base64.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Original SMTP supports email addresses composed of ASCII characters only, which is inconvenient for users whose native script is not Latin based, or who use diacritic not in the ASCII character set.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This limitation was alleviated via extensions enabling UTF-8 in address names.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] RFC 5336 introduced experimental `UTF8SMTP` command and later was superseded by RFC 6531 that introduced `SMTPUTF8` command.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] These extensions provide support for multi-byte and non-ASCII characters in email addresses, such as those with diacritics and other language characters such as Greek and Chinese.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Current support is limited, but there is strong interest in broad adoption of RFC 6531 and the related RFCs in countries like China that have a large user base where Latin (ASCII) is a foreign script.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Like SMTP, ESMTP is a protocol used to transport Internet mail.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] It is used as both an inter-server transport protocol and (with restricted behavior enforced) a mail submission protocol.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The main identification feature for ESMTP clients is to open a transmission with the command `EHLO` (Extended HELLO), rather than `HELO` (Hello, the original RFC 821 standard).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A server will respond with success (code 250), failure (code 550) or error (code 500, 501, 502, 504, or 421), depending on its configuration.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] An ESMTP server returns the code 250 OK in a multi-line reply with its domain and a list of keywords to indicate supported extensions.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A RFC 821 compliant server returns error code 500, allowing ESMTP clients to try either `HELO` or `QUIT`.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Each service extension is defined in an approved format in subsequent RFCs and registered with the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA).
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The first definitions were the RFC 821 optional services: `SEND`, `SOML` (Send or Mail), `SAML` (Send and Mail), `EXPN`, `HELP`, and `TURN`.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The format of additional SMTP verbs was set and for new parameters in `MAIL` and `RCPT`.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The ESMTP format was restated in RFC 2821 (superseding RFC 821) and updated to the latest definition in RFC 5321 in 2008.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Support for the `EHLO` command in servers became mandatory, and `HELO` designated a required fallback.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Non-standard, unregistered, service extensions can be used by bilateral agreement, these services are indicated by an `EHLO` message keyword starting with "X", and with any additional parameters or verbs similarly marked.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] They are presented here in capitalized form for emphasis only.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] An SMTP server that requires a specific capitalization method is a violation of the standard.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The SMTP-AUTH extension provides an access control mechanism.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] It consists of an authentication step through which the client effectively logs into the mail server during the process of sending mail.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Servers that support SMTP-AUTH can usually be configured to require clients to use this extension, ensuring the true identity of the sender is known.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The SMTP-AUTH extension is defined in RFC 4954.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] SMTP-AUTH can be used to allow legitimate users to relay mail while denying relay service to unauthorized users, such as spammers.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] It does not necessarily guarantee the authenticity of either the SMTP envelope sender or the RFC 2822 "From:" header.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] For example, spoofing, in which one sender masquerades as someone else, is still possible with SMTP-AUTH unless the server is configured to limit message from-addresses to addresses this AUTHed user is authorized for.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The SMTP-AUTH extension also allows one mail server to indicate to another that the sender has been authenticated when relaying mail.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In general this requires the recipient server to trust the sending server, meaning that this aspect of SMTP-AUTH is rarely used on the Internet.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Mail delivery can occur both over plain text and encrypted connections, however the communicating parties might not know in advance of other party's ability to use secure channel.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The STARTTLS extensions enables supporting SMTP servers to notify connecting clients that it supports TLS encrypted communication and offers the opportunity for clients to upgrade their connection by sending the STARTTLS command.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Servers supporting the extension do not inherently gain any security benefits from its implementation on its own, as upgrading to a TLS encrypted session is dependent on the connecting client deciding to exercise this option, hence the term *opportunistic* TLS.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] STARTTLS is effective only against passive observation attacks, since the STARTTLS negotiation happens in plain text and an active attacker can trivially remove STARTTLS commands.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] This type of man-in-the-middle attack is sometimes referred to as STRIPTLS, where the encryption negotiation information sent from one end never reaches the other.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In this scenario both parties take the invalid or unexpected responses as indication that the other does not properly support STARTTLS, defaulting to traditional plain-text mail transfer.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Note that STARTTLS is also defined for IMAP and POP3 in other RFCs, but these protocols serve different purposes: SMTP is used for communication between message transfer agents, while IMAP and POP3 are for end clients and message transfer agents.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In 2014 the Electronic Frontier Foundation began "STARTTLS Everywhere" project that, similarly to "HTTPS Everywhere" list, allowed relying parties to discover others supporting secure communication without prior communication.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The project stopped accepting submissions on 29 April 2021, and EFF recommended switching to DANE and MTA-STS for discovering information on peers' TLS support.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] RFC 8314 officially declared plain text obsolete and recommend always using TLS for mail submission and access, adding ports with implicit TLS.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] RFC 7672 introduced the ability for DNS records to declare the encryption capabilities of a mail server.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Utilising DNSSEC, mail server operators are able to publish a hash of their TLS certificate, thereby mitigating the possibility of unencrypted communications.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Microsoft expects to enable full SMTP DANE support for Exchange Online customers by the end of 2024.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] A newer 2018 RFC 8461 called "SMTP MTA Strict Transport Security (MTA-STS)" aims to address the problem of active adversaries by defining a protocol for mail servers to declare their ability to use secure channels in specific files on the server and specific DNS TXT records.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The relying party would regularly check existence of such record, and cache it for the amount of time specified in the record and never communicate over insecure channels until record expires.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Note that MTA-STS records apply only to SMTP traffic between mail servers while communications between a user's client and the mail server are protected by Transport Layer Security with SMTP/MSA, IMAP, POP3, or HTTPS in combination with an organizational or technical policy.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Essentially, MTA-STS is a means to extend such a policy to third parties.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In April 2019 Google Mail announced support for MTA-STS.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Protocols designed to securely deliver messages can fail due to misconfigurations or deliberate active interference, leading to undelivered messages or delivery over unencrypted or unauthenticated channels.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] RFC 8460 "SMTP TLS Reporting" describes a reporting mechanism and format for sharing statistics and specific information about potential failures with recipient domains.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Recipient domains can then use this information to both detect potential attacks and diagnose unintentional misconfigurations.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] In April 2019 Gmail announced support for SMTP TLS Reporting.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] The original design of SMTP had no facility to authenticate senders, or check that servers were authorized to send on their behalf, with the result that email spoofing is possible, and commonly used in email spam and phishing.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Occasional proposals are made to modify SMTP extensively or replace it completely.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] One example of this is Internet Mail 2000, but neither it, nor any other has made much headway in the face of the network effect of the huge installed base of classic SMTP.
[src:nodemailer-email/simple-mail-transfer-protocol] Instead, mail servers now use a range of techniques, such as stricter enforcement of standards such as RFC 5322, DomainKeys Identified Mail, Sender Policy Framework and DMARC, DNSBLs and greylisting to reject or quarantine suspicious emails.
